"Completed.\n\n## Bottleneck found with `EXPLAIN ANALYZE`\n\nAccording to the PostgreSQL MCP `EXPLAIN ANALYZE` result, the original query took:\n\n| Version | Execution time | Plan cost |\n|---|---:|---:|\n| Original query before optimization | `698.708 ms` | `129863.09..129863.58` |\n| Original query after index | `25.173 ms` | `26347.49..26347.98` |\n| Rewritten optimized query | `10.239 ms` | `1683.05..1683.53` |\n\nThe main bottleneck was the two correlated subqueries:\n\n```sql\nSELECT COUNT(*) FROM payment p2 ...\nSELECT SUM(amount) FROM payment p3 ...\n```\n\nThey were doing repeated `Seq Scan` operations on `payment`, each executed `583` times.\n\n## Database optimization applied\n\nThe `payment` table had no index on `customer_id`, so I created:\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_payment_customer_id\nON public.payment (customer_id);\n```\n\nAfter this, the original query switched from repeated sequential scans to bitmap/index scans and dropped to `25.173 ms`.\n\n## Recommended optimized query\n\nThis version removes the repeated correlated subqueries and computes everything in one grouped pass over `payment`:\n\n```sql\nWITH customer_payment_stats AS (\n    SELECT\n        p.customer_id,\n        COUNT(*) AS total_payments,\n        SUM(p.amount) AS total_spent,\n        AVG(p.amount) AS avg_payment,\n        COUNT(DISTINCT EXTRACT(month FROM p.payment_date)) AS active_months,\n        MAX(p.payment_date) AS last_payment,\n        MIN(p.payment_date) AS first_payment,\n        COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE p.amount > 5.0) AS high_value_payments,\n        SUM(p.amount) FILTER (WHERE p.payment_date >= '2007-03-01') AS recent_spending\n    FROM payment p\n    GROUP BY p.customer_id\n    HAVING COUNT(*) >= 10\n)\nSELECT\n    c.customer_id,\n    c.first_name,\n    c.last_name,\n    c.email,\n    s.total_payments,\n    s.total_spent,\n    s.avg_payment,\n    s.active_months,\n    s.last_payment,\n    s.first_payment,\n    s.high_value_payments,\n    s.recent_spending\nFROM customer c\nJOIN customer_payment_stats s ON c.customer_id = s.customer_id\nWHERE c.active = 1\nORDER BY s.total_spent DESC, s.total_payments DESC;\n```\n\n## Accuracy verification\n\nI compared the original and optimized result sets with `EXCEPT` in both directions.\n\nResult from PostgreSQL MCP `execute_sql`:\n\n```text\noriginal_rows: 583\noptimized_rows: 583\noriginal_minus_optimized: 0\noptimized_minus_original: 0\n```\n\nSo the optimized query returns the same results.\n\n## Summary\n\n- Added `idx_payment_customer_id` on `payment(customer_id)`.\n- Rewrote the query to avoid repeated correlated subqueries.\n- Runtime improved from `698.708 ms` to `10.239 ms`.\n- Result accuracy was verified: `0` row differences."